This section provides a compact overview of the most important steps when creating a template. For further information, please refer to the respective chapters in the section below.

## Create file, enter text, saving
- After logging in to the Business Designer application, click the button  ![](data:image/png;base64,) to create a new file.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The newly created file has this structure:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Enter text

The cursor is positioned at the beginning of the template and you can start entering the fixed texts of the template. With the text input a new text element will be automatically created and it is located in a "Block" element.

As soon as you start a new line with the Enter key, a new block with a new text element is automatically created. Empty lines are also block elements, but they do not contain text elements.

Text elements can be of any length (automatic line break). However, they cannot consist of several paragraphs. See details [Text elements, text editing](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-structure-of-templates-working-with-content-1#text-elements-text-editing).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Save the file with Ctrl+S or with the icon  ![](data:image/png;base64,). Business Designer files have the ending .ITX

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note:

*You_ ****cannot ****_place content (text, images, etc.) anywhere on the page. If you need this - e.g. to place the company address on the left and the company logo in the header on the right - you have to work with tables. For more information on tables see the Chapter. *[Tables](/doxee-platform/docs/tables).

## Autosave
It is possible to save a file automatically in a time interval defined in the configuration. Autosave can be activated in the user settings (tool icon) under "Autosave". The default interval is 30 seconds. Automatic saving only works if the normal save function is available - if a versioned file is not checked out, it cannot be saved automatically, because only "save as" is available.

## Connect the template with XML test data
To add dynamic content, the fields of the data source must be available (e.g. fields of your customer database). The template must be linked to an XML file which has the structure of the data source and contains a test record.

- Click on *Data *on the right, then *Manage Test Data *or *Add your first Test Data*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Define data input: click on *Data Input Variables *and then on the plus icon on the right.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Add test case: Click on the *Assign *button on the right.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Select the XML file.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Click on *Test Cases*, and you will see that the XML file has been added as "Test Case 1". This item is not activated by default. If you want to use the test case, you must activate it with the toggle/slider button.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Rename the data input if necessary (Edit icon).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Click the *Design *button on the toolbar to switch back to the editor. 

With Version 6.4 Business Designer supports big XML Files as input Data.

## Insert data fields
- The test case is now available in the *Data *section of the editing area (Palette) - select it.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Use the arrow icons to open the desired layer. This will display the data fields.

- The data fields are dynamic elements that can now be dragged to the desired position in the template, whereby they are inserted into the respective block (e.g. empty row).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Just like text elements, dynamic elements can also be placed next to each other (Inline Elements):

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Dynamic elements can also be dragged into text elements. This will split the text element automatically into two text elements and places the dynamic element in between.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- If necessary, drag in additional text elements (from the palette, section *Standard*), e.g. to add necessary spaces.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Make sure that the structure of the content is correct and contains only necessary elements.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Insert conditional content
For text, numbers or other content that depends on specific data in the database - such as the correct salutation based on gender - use conditional elements.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

A condition element consists of branches. For example, in the case of a gender-specific form of an address:

- If gender is female, then "Dear Madam &lt;name&gt;" (branch 1)

- If gender is male, then "Dear Sir &lt;name&gt;" (branch 2)

- Otherwise "Dear customer" (branch 3 or else condition, e.g. if the gender is not entered in a data record).

Procedure:

- Drag a condition element to the desired position in the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

This creates a first condition branch together with the condition element.

- Drag another condition branch **on top **of the condition. Do the same for further necessary condition branches.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Enter conditions: Click on the **word ***condition branch *to set which branch to edit, then click on the ?-icon to open the XPath input window.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

- Enter the condition directly as XPath expression or use the rule editor: *Open in Rules Editor*.

- Assemble the XPath expression in the rule editor. To insert data fields, first go to *Data *on the left, then select the existing test case on the middle bar and open the list of fields, then drag the field to the right editing area. For the example above, the field "gender" has been dragged in and it was completed with the required comparison expression, in this case: = "w"

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Close the rule editor and save the expression with *Apply*. In the example above, the same procedure is followed for the second condition branch, the comparison expression is = "m"

The Else Condition - in this example the third condition branch - always remains completely empty.

> Note:

*When entering functions, etc. please pay attention to the spelling (case-sensitive)*

- The condition branches must now be completed with the necessary text fields: To do this, drag a text element **on top **of the respective branch element, either directly into the template or into the outline. The cursor is now positioned in the text element and the text can be entered. Or you can enter text by clicking on the conditional branch and start typing the text, a text element will be automatically created in the conditional branch.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Add dynamic elements to the branch expression if necessary: the name field behind the text field is dragged into the condition branch here.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

The finished condition of the example would look like this:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Insert images
To upload images to the Doxee Content Repository, use a right click on the file view  select "Upload here" to upload any file.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Drag an image element onto the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Double-click the image frame

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Select the image file.

- Change the image size if necessary: either by dragging the sizing handles or by entering the dimensions under *Style &amp; Properties *&gt; *Image*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Images are scaled proportionally by default; if you want to change the aspect ratio, toggle with the lock icon, then height and width can be entered independently.

You can also insert images by drag&amp;drop them directly from your desktop or another source.

## Formatting
- Select an element

The available format settings depend on the selected element. Make sure that (only) the desired block or the element inside the block is selected, preferably by selecting it in the outline. For details see [Marking elements](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-structure-of-templates-working-with-content-1#marking-elements).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Formats always refer to elements. You can mark text parts (e.g. single words) within a text element to format them differently from the rest of the text (e.g. set bold or italic) - in this case the text element is automatically split and a corresponding number of separate text elements will be created.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Set formats You can then set the desired formats under *Style &amp; Properties *in the panel on the right, such as the font or paragraph alignment under *Fonts*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note:

*Only the most common format settings are displayed in the menu. Under Advanced you will find all the available XSL-FO standard attributes for the element.*

*Instead of working with direct formats, you can also work with style sheets, which can save time and contribute to the uniform appearance of texts - see *[Formats and style sheets](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-formats-and-style-sheets-1).

## Test template (preview), activate test case
- Set the output format "PDF" (or some other format) in the toolbar with the arrow icon on the preview button, then click on the preview button to test how the PDF document (or other formats) created with the template would look like.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

However, the actual test data set is not yet taken into account, so that e.g. the inserted name fields remain empty and only the "else" case is taken in case of conditions.

- Activate the test case to test dynamic contents: go to *Data *on the right and click on *Manage Test Data*, or click on Test Data in the toolbar and activate the toggle/slider on the right side of the assigned test case - it will turn orange when activated.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

If you generate the preview PDF again, the data from the activated test case will be used and the document for this test data set will be generated correctly.

## Testing conditions, multiple test data sets
To test condition branches you need to have and activate several test cases. You can assign any number of XML files:

- Click on the + icon at *Test Cases *in the test data management. "Test case 2" is now displayed below.

- Select "Test Case 2" (click on the empty space next to the name) and then - as with the first test case - select the XML file with the *assign *button on the right.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If you now activate the second test case, two PDFs with the respective data will be created during the preview.

> Note:

*The XML file can be modified. If there is only one test file available, you can simply change the data here (on the right side), use the button on the right to save the changes and generate the document again.*

*![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*

## Insert and format date
To insert a dynamic date, a dynamic value with an XPath function is used.

- Insert a "Dynamic Value" element.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Open the Rules Editor

- Click on *Functions *then "Date, Time, Duration" category and find the "current-date" function. Drag it into the Editing Area. You can test the function with the *Run *button

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- The current-date function generates a date in Anglo-American format, which also contains the time. To control the date format, the date function must be inserted into another function. To do this, find the "format-date" function in the same category and drag it in front of the current-date function in the editing area.

- Add the desired date format in the current-date function, e.g. '[D01].[M01].[Y]' to obtain a date in this form: 31.07.2020. The complete syntax is: format-date(current-date(), '[D01].[M01].[Y]')

D01 stands for the day, with a leading zero, M for month, Y for year. The format '[Y]/[M]/[D]' would generate a date in the form 2020/7/31. The specification for the weekday is [F]. [Mn] would result in "July".

- To set the date right-aligned, select the block containing the date element and set the appropriate alignment in the *Fonts *format category.

- Check the generated PDF document to make sure the date and the date format are correct.

## Errors
If the template contains a dynamic element that cannot be resolved, e.g. if an XPath expression is syntactically incorrect or not applicable to the data, the output document cant be generated. When trying to create a PDF, an error is displayed. See also [Check dynamic](#_bookmark54) [elements](/doxee-platform/docs/dynamic-content#check-dynamic-elements).

The errors are displayed under *Show problems and events *(tools icon). If you click on a specific error or event, the affected element is marked in the outline.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Arrange elements
In the default page layout of XSL-FO, elements are only placed either below each other or next to each other in the same line. If a different arrangement or exact positioning of contents is required, e.g. several text lines next to an image, tables are almost always used for this purpose. For details see [Tables](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-tables-1). XSL-FO theoretically also provides absolute positioning, with which elements can be moved or placed on top of each other, even multi-column text is possible.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Copy &amp; Pasting content from internal sources
If a text is copied from **Business Designer Editor **itself and pasted into the Business Designer Editor with Ctrl+V, the options: *Keep structure and formatting (local) *, *Keep structure (local) *and *Paste as plain text *are available.

**Keep structure and formatting (local) **= all elements such as tables, conditions and images and formatting like fonts, colors, etc. are retained. What is pasted is basically a snippet of the template file (ITX).

**Keep structure (local) **= all elements such as tables, conditions and images are retained as best as possible. Formatting is ignored - not retained. What is pasted is basically a snippet of the template file (ITX) with most formatting removed.

**Paste as plain text **= only the text without pictures, tables and colors etc. will be inserted. The behavior with this function is as if a text was inserted into the Windows Notepad / Notepad. Plain text is extracted from the snippet of the template file (ITX) and then pasted.

## Copy &amp; Pasting content from external sources
If a text is copied from **MS Word **and pasted into the Business Designer Editor with Ctrl+V, the options: *Keep structure and formatting (RTF) *, *Keep structure (RTF) *and *Paste as plain text *are available.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Keep structure and formatting (RTF) **= all elements such as tables and images and formatting like fonts, colors, etc. are retained as best as possible. (Best possible because it can happen, for example, that a font is not installed and the Business Designer therefore switches to a default font).

**Keep structure (RTF) **= all elements such as tables and images are retained as best as possible. Formatting is ignored - not retained.

**Paste as plain text **= only the text without pictures, tables and colors etc. will be inserted. The behavior with this function is as if a text was inserted into the Windows Notepad / Notepad.

If the text is pasted with a right click via the context menu, further options are available: the existing block / text can be replaced, or the copied text is pasted at the end of the element. Both options can be selected with or without formatting.

![](data:image/png;base64,)![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note

Due to technical limitations the source format is HTML if the text is pasted with a right click via the context menu also when it is copied from **MS Word**. The result may be different compared to the result of Ctrl+V. In this case the options: *Keep structure and formatting (HTML) *, *Keep structure (HTML) *and *Paste as plain text *.

When copying **content from the browser **with Ctrl+V, the options *Keep structure and formatting (HTML) *, *Keep structure (HTML) *and *Paste as plain text *are available.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Keep structure and formatting (HTML) **= as when copying MS Word content, the source elements and formatting are retained as best as possible.

**Keep structure (HTML) **= as when copying MS Word content, the source elements are retained as best as possible. Formatting is ignored - not retained.

**Paste as plain text **= No tables, images, etc. will be inserted.

If **images from web **are copied and pasted with Ctrl+V, the options *Paste as picture *, *Keep structure and formatting (HTML) *and *Keep structure (HTML) *are available.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Paste as picture **= The picture is inserted as Base64

**Keep structure and formatting (HTML) **= Image is inserted formatted with its original link

**Keep structure (HTML) **= Image is inserted with its original link without formatting

> Note

*Due to the security settings in Firefox, it may happen that no content can be pasted from the clipboard. Enter "about:config" in the address bar, click on "Accept risk and continue" then search for the setting name "clipboard" and change the following settings as indicated in the table. After the change, we do recommend refreshing the browser tab with the open Business Designer.*

## Output Configuration
The output configuration can be used to control which output components are included in the XSL generation. The output configuration is located in the design view in the right panel below the palette and data.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

When creating a predefined package via the start page, e.g. a template part package, the appropriate output configuration is set automatically and taken into account during XSL generation. In the selection under *Output Components *you can choose one of the predefined

output configurations or set up your own custom configuration with your own name. The components are selected by activating the checkboxes. The output configuration has an influence on the opening of the templates. Depending on the components, the corresponding view will be opened. For example, a template with the output configuration *Template part package *will opened directly in template part view.

> Note

Not all combinations of output components result in a renderable document! The template or one of the referenced templates must export the *Page Sequence *element.

## External Resource Management
You can find the _External Resource Management in the left toolbar under "Other" when clicking on the arrow icon to find it. It is used to display and manage external resources. In the external resources management all ITX files linked with the template are listed.

Depending on the output configuration, the corresponding elements will be displayed.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

By clicking on the arrow icon next to the name of the listed external resource, further information can be displayed such as information about nested elements. Nested elements will be displayed graphically in one card. You can open the files by clicking on the folder icon or delete them by clicking on the recycle bin. Above the listed external resources you can add new files. On the right side, if you have selected or clicked on an external resource, you can edit various attributes. For example, you can change and adjust the path (src) of the resource.

> Note

*You can only edit the attributes of external resources on the first level. Attributes of nested resources must be edited on the corresponding level above.*

You can recognize nested files by the listed parent file in brackets in grey next to the name.
